<subSubSection id="E0C50C8607D8F2742DEA4A3D21790EEE" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="339CF3735DD37E2250958B453AA3E6F6" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7D9005032F0E362AD5D611AB1BC840F5" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">
<taxonomicName id="6A7849699BF9A6F47EC41848FEBA6A24" authorityName="Wood" authorityYear="2020" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Andrena" higherTaxonomySource="CoL" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Andrena sparsipunctata" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="sparsipunctata">
<emphasis id="F959BFD167FBDAB3B0D6381F655B5B1F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Andrena sparsipunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
can be easily placed into the 
<taxonomicName id="F808BE92120A115E8274C96B44521360" authority="Dours, 1873" authorityName="Dours" authorityYear="1873" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Campylogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Campylogaster" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="14D64A937971A6B1A599E02077A61B52" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Campylogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
because of the large, dense, and clear punctures on the episternum combined with its large body size. However, recent evidence shows that 
<taxonomicName id="ADF491251BB7885B80C5F74DA7271290" authority="Dours, 1873" authorityName="Dours" authorityYear="1873" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Campylogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Campylogaster" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="21D8C5A03CD2A739897354D5F5EFC2C7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Campylogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is strongly polyphyletic, and the species in northwestern Africa do not fall close to 
<taxonomicName id="3664C974B7A9DD51BA7984AEC5A54D7B" genus="A." lsidName="A. (Campylogaster) erberi" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="erberi" subGenus="Campylogaster">A. (Campylogaster) erberi</taxonomicName>
Morawitz, 1871, the type species of 
<taxonomicName id="A299306405C6DB7BE79E18919D26AA8F" authority="Dours, 1873" authorityName="Dours" authorityYear="1873" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Campylogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Campylogaster" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="8EF641DE8A81953D83051F2FD9D6434D" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Campylogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
that differs by its tormentose pilosity. A new subgenus is probably needed for the species around 
<taxonomicName id="B51EB30858FEE2D022F0AFDC676DF0BA" genus="A." lsidName="A. sparsipunctata" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="sparsipunctata">
<emphasis id="C3FCB6E40AE787C5239842AE5DB24DEF" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. sparsipunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<bibRefCitation id="BB3371DFF568925F9D0917297F0BDD72" DOI="https://doi.org/10.1101/2020.06.09.103556" author="Pisanty, G" journalOrPublisher="Gounouilhou, Bordeaux" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" refId="B28" refString="Pisanty, G, Richter, R, Martin, T, Dettman, J, Cardinal, S, 2020. Molecular phylogeny and historical biogeography of andrenine bees (Hymenoptera: Andrenidae). bioRxiv. https://doi.org/10.1101/2020.06.09.103556" title="Molecular phylogeny and historical biogeography of andrenine bees (Hymenoptera: Andrenidae). bioRxiv." url="https://doi.org/10.1101/2020.06.09.103556" year="2020">Pisanty et al. 2020</bibRefCitation>
). Against this context, it is close to the two most widespread 
<taxonomicName id="1AF6D3C18BBBE0DA11320CA50F8452CC" authority="Dours, 1873" authorityName="Dours" authorityYear="1873" class="Insecta" family="Andrenidae" genus="Campylogaster" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Campylogaster" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="0557C93D71DF46ED0C6A0CDE90B7D2B0" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">Campylogaster</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
species in North Africa, 
<taxonomicName id="95D17E5ABDE006B2DA5FC5AC43846C2B" genus="A." lsidName="A. pruinosa subsp. succinea" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="subSpecies" species="pruinosa" subSpecies="succinea">A. pruinosa Erichson, 1835 ssp. succinea</taxonomicName>
Dours, 1872 and 
<taxonomicName id="20AA87C423C601C6DEB55397719F81D2" genus="A." lsidName="A. caroli" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="caroli">
<emphasis id="0817E50F24580E8DDE01EB9BFF073FCA" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. caroli</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<normalizedToken id="A109D4F102E3792B7B45ECE6A39E386D" originalValue="Pérez">Perez</normalizedToken>
, 1895, both of which are also stained red over the majority of the metasoma. The female of 
<taxonomicName id="4FFE8AC9568DDCF42012DFBC96DC570C" genus="A." lsidName="A. sparsipunctata" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="sparsipunctata">
<emphasis id="10C62931DC9FCE4B876F1FD8E59CB72F" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. sparsipunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is instantly recognisable because the punctures of the first tergite are sparse, separated by 2-4 puncture diameters (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="1E678CC67058CB55C6154B03FCD809E9" captionStart="Figures 13–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 20. Andrena (Campylogaster) sparsipunctata sp. nov. 13 female profile 14 female mesonotum in semi-profile 15 female head dorsal view 16 female tergites. Andrena (Campylogaster) pruinosa succinea Dours, 1872 17 female head dorsal view 18 female tergites. Andrena caroli Perez, 1895 19 female head dorsal view 20 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures13-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460644" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">16</figureCitation>
) whereas in the other two species the punctures are dense and separated by 1-2 puncture diameters (Figs 
<figureCitation id="F13D7541AA2A2A51DD14CEE9599A96C4" captionStart="Figures 13–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 20. Andrena (Campylogaster) sparsipunctata sp. nov. 13 female profile 14 female mesonotum in semi-profile 15 female head dorsal view 16 female tergites. Andrena (Campylogaster) pruinosa succinea Dours, 1872 17 female head dorsal view 18 female tergites. Andrena caroli Perez, 1895 19 female head dorsal view 20 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures13-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460644" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">18</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="6943D153F9C865E4217303DE154027DB" captionStart="Figures 13–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 20. Andrena (Campylogaster) sparsipunctata sp. nov. 13 female profile 14 female mesonotum in semi-profile 15 female head dorsal view 16 female tergites. Andrena (Campylogaster) pruinosa succinea Dours, 1872 17 female head dorsal view 18 female tergites. Andrena caroli Perez, 1895 19 female head dorsal view 20 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures13-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460644" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">20</figureCitation>
). Moreover, the foveae of 
<taxonomicName id="DBA9F9DE8A695DF898C19EB4B5545914" genus="A." lsidName="A. sparsipunctata" pageId="0" pageNumber="31" rank="species" species="sparsipunctata">
<emphasis id="B794E79A2A60B1A96B3543545E85C537" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">A. sparsipunctata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
females are narrow and depart from the inner eye margins so that at the top of the compound eye they are separated from the compound eye by a distance subequal to the width of a fovea itself (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="E9FA627DD65F794CCECFDF7AA772EF43" captionStart="Figures 13–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 20. Andrena (Campylogaster) sparsipunctata sp. nov. 13 female profile 14 female mesonotum in semi-profile 15 female head dorsal view 16 female tergites. Andrena (Campylogaster) pruinosa succinea Dours, 1872 17 female head dorsal view 18 female tergites. Andrena caroli Perez, 1895 19 female head dorsal view 20 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures13-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460644" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">15</figureCitation>
), whereas in the other two species the foveae are never clearly separated from the top of the compound eye (Figs 
<figureCitation id="5ED372C192CC93C20AEEABB6E48887D6" captionStart="Figures 13–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 20. Andrena (Campylogaster) sparsipunctata sp. nov. 13 female profile 14 female mesonotum in semi-profile 15 female head dorsal view 16 female tergites. Andrena (Campylogaster) pruinosa succinea Dours, 1872 17 female head dorsal view 18 female tergites. Andrena caroli Perez, 1895 19 female head dorsal view 20 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures13-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460644" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">17</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation id="ED01F0A16DA364B74720ED046686F07D" captionStart="Figures 13–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 20. Andrena (Campylogaster) sparsipunctata sp. nov. 13 female profile 14 female mesonotum in semi-profile 15 female head dorsal view 16 female tergites. Andrena (Campylogaster) pruinosa succinea Dours, 1872 17 female head dorsal view 18 female tergites. Andrena caroli Perez, 1895 19 female head dorsal view 20 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures13-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460644" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">19</figureCitation>
). The scutal hairs are also normal, not squamous (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="48CF629FC422A9C42399592122CCBB29" captionStart="Figures 13–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 20. Andrena (Campylogaster) sparsipunctata sp. nov. 13 female profile 14 female mesonotum in semi-profile 15 female head dorsal view 16 female tergites. Andrena (Campylogaster) pruinosa succinea Dours, 1872 17 female head dorsal view 18 female tergites. Andrena caroli Perez, 1895 19 female head dorsal view 20 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures13-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460644" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">15</figureCitation>
), strongly contrasting with the squamous hairs of the other two species (Figs 
<figureCitation id="DFD70DE1A6085FDCE80D62E439683808" captionStart="Figures 13–20" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figures 13 - 20. Andrena (Campylogaster) sparsipunctata sp. nov. 13 female profile 14 female mesonotum in semi-profile 15 female head dorsal view 16 female tergites. Andrena (Campylogaster) pruinosa succinea Dours, 1872 17 female head dorsal view 18 female tergites. Andrena caroli Perez, 1895 19 female head dorsal view 20 female tergites." figureDoi="10.3897/zookeys.974.54794.figures13-20" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/460644" pageId="0" pageNumber="31">17</figureCitation>
, 
